## Configuration Files

### 1. Provider Setup (`terra.tf`)

This file configures the necessary Terraform providers. It explicitly locks the AWS and Random provider versions and creates a provider alias named `ubuntu_IND` specifically targeting the Mumbai region (`ap-south-1`).

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    # Telling Terraform which providers to download and use
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = ">= 6.42.0"
    }

    random = {
      source  = "hashicorp/random"
      version = "3.8.1"
    }
  }
}

# Configuring the AWS region
provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
  alias  = "ubuntu_IND"
}

```

### 2. Variables (`var.tf`)

We define the instance type input here. For testing validation failures, the default is intentionally set to an invalid type (`t100.micro`).

```hcl
variable "instance_type" {
  type = string
  #default = "t2.micro"
   default = "t100.micro"
}

```

### 3. Local Values (`local.tf`)

This file acts as our governance gatekeeper, holding an array of instance families we officially allow in our environment.

```hcl
locals {
  allowed_instance_types=["t2.micro","t3.micro"]
}

```

### 4. Data Sources (`data.tf`)

This fetches the most up-to-date official Canonical Ubuntu 22.04 LTS HVM AMI from the India region provider.

```hcl
data "aws_ami" "own_ami_ubuntu_IND" {
  most_recent = true
  owners      = ["099720109477"] # Canonical official owner ID
  provider    = aws.ubuntu_IND   # Use India provider alias

  # Filter by AMI name pattern
  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-jammy-22.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  # Ensure virtualization type is HVM
  filter {
    name   = "virtualization-type"
    values = ["hvm"]
  }
}

```

### 5. Compute Resources (`compute.tf`)

This is where the magic happens. The EC2 resource definition includes two custom `precondition` blocks within its `lifecycle` configuration to validate both the AMI architecture and the chosen instance type before deployment.

```hcl
resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  count         = 1
  ami           = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND.id
  instance_type = var.instance_type
  lifecycle {
    precondition {
      condition     = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND.architecture == "x86_64"
      #condition     = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND.architecture == "abc"
      error_message = "Mentioned AMI is from bad place as it is invalid"
    }
    precondition {
      condition     = contains(local.allowed_instance_types,var.instance_type)
      error_message = "Mentioned instances has virus so it is not allowed to launch"
    }

  }

  tags = {
    Name = "own_terra-serial-${count.index}"
  }
}

```

### 6. Outputs (`out.tf`)

Exposes all configuration details for both the EC2 instance and the fetched AMI resource for quick debugging.

```hcl
output "ec2_full_details" {
  value = aws_instance.my_ec2
}

output "AMI_full_details" {
  value = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND
}
